2026-04-16 12:15:06 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['internal wiring of power supply module (battery positive terminal, PSU LED anode, series resistor connection, and PSU + output cable)'] hypothesis_explanation='The new battery has 12 V at the holder, but only ~0.012 V appears both across the PSU LED branch and at the module outputs. Visual inspection shows that the battery positive terminal is not connected to anything, the LED anode is floating, the LED cathode is tied to the negative output cable, and the series resistor is tied only to the positive output cable. The negative battery terminal is tied to the negative output cable, but there is no path from the battery positive terminal to the positive output cable, nor to the LED branch. This miswiring leaves the whole downstream system effectively unpowered and keeps the PSU indicator LED off. Correct wiring should connect the battery positive terminal to the PSU + output cable and to the LED-series-resistor node, with the LED anode properly connected so the indicator sits across the supply. Restoring that wiring (repairing the miswired connections within the power supply module) should supply 12 V to the control modules and the load so the system can operate.'
